  "target_response": {
    "text": "They're different signals. Your respiratory rate is 15.8 breaths per minute — how many breaths you take each minute while asleep — above your 30-day average of 14.6, but only slightly. It has nothing to do with heart rate. That one is separate: your resting heart rate is 56 bpm, a touch over your 30-day average of 55.4 bpm — the number in the 50s you were thinking of. A small respiratory-rate rise like this often lines up with a late meal, a stuffy room, or the first hint of a cold; it only becomes interesting if it stays elevated several nights in a row alongside other shifts. This morning the rest of the picture is ordinary — your HRV is 62 ms, close to your 30-day average of 62.8 ms — so file it as a note, not a warning.",
